metadata.name: Asterium #59
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: Cloverfield #120
metadata.description:
"Nature is the source of all true knowledge".

Have you ever taken the time to look, deeply look, at all the details in a humble patch of grass ?

In this tiny microcosm, a constant, fierce battle is going on, day after day, plants reaching out for sun, down for access to soil, fighting for survival. Smaller grasses form groups, alliances making it harder for taller ones to take over. Dead leaves remind us that some of them lost the fight, fallen warriors who, soon enough, will be forgotten too. Growth, decay, life, death, the endless cycle, right in front of our eyes.

It is fascinating, and, for me at least, an endless source of inspiration.

It is my hope that, through this project, you will take the time to take a closer look at nature, and that, as the pale blue dot we call home keeps getting drier and drier, remember that even humble patches of grass should not be taken for granted.


Key commands:
's' - save as png
'b' - make the background transparent (for printing)
'1', '2, '4' - set the pixel density, for resolutions up to 8000x8000

This updated version of the project should render on mobile devices, albeit with slightly reduced quality. 
If you want to save the image for printing, I recommend you do so on desktop.

metadata.name: Somewhere In Between #142
metadata.description:
Does entropy across time look the same in a universe different to ours? 

The universe is full of potential energy, recognized as a difference across some scale. Differences in pressure, temperature, state, all act in pursuit of equilibrium. Given enough time, a closed system will eventually fall into an even dispersal. Somewhere in between is some yet-to-be-determined point at which beautiful unexpected forms emerge.

This system takes the standard model of equal exchange and throws it off balance, so each reaction will randomly decide which side has an advantage over the other, and instead of dispersal, one force will win out.

In this system, do similar complex patterns appear? Will we see anything new that doesn't appear with our usual rules?

I found this idea very interesting, that even with no law towards chaos, actually the opposite, we can still end in formlessness. A blank end where no pixel differs from another.

I think that through observation of the world and experimenting with its concepts, we can learn far more about life than just the processes we're studying. 

I'd be very curious to hear about what you take away from the work, and where your somewhere might be <3

Press the space bar to add another step toward chaos
Press ‘p’ to add 10 steps (enters mode 2)
Press ‘f’ to enter an animation that will run for 1,056,993,066,125,486,216,810,417,723,659,732,792 years
Press 'f' again to pause
Press ‘a’ to add a new section of order to the system, you can use this when one state has taken over the canvas

Press ’s’ to save a png
Press ‘1’ or ‘2’ to begin render between the default 3200x4000px or 6400x8000px

Created by Chris McCully using p5.js, chroma.js, and GLSL.

Built to run best on Chrome and Chromium based browsers.

metadata.name: Illusion City #300
metadata.description:
Illusion City reflects the variety of Istanbul by its different and divergent zones, day and night, humid summers and ice cold winters, colorful neighborhoods and giant plazas, its never ending human and vehicle traffic.

This series is an expression of how we experience this city, kind of like a love and hate relationship. The city that is a cradle of civilizations now has become a concrete jungle. Our beautiful city and its citizens are now trying to find their own balance in this state of chaos.

We wanted to express these complex emotions with a long-form generative artwork since it is the most suitable medium to explore every possible combination of emotions we have about our city. 

Best experienced in full screen.

Probabilities;

- 3 pre-made color palettes, 1 generative color palette

- 3 blend modes

- 3 topping placements

- 8 different particle angle compositions

- Several grid sizes and edges

- An intentionally kept in glitch (rare)

In live mode, press ‘s’ to save as .png (2000 x 2666 px )

It can take up to a minute to render or longer in low-performance computers. Enjoy the process!

Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, July 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Quadrangle of My Being #122
metadata.description:
This project began as an exploration of how human beings across all sorts of cultures respond in remarkably similar ways in terms of associating sounds with shapes.  That’s a project I will have to come back to. Along the way, the outputs started to remind me of landforms seen from high above and topographical maps of imaginary terrain - the terrain of my own being.

Though the work is algorithmic through and through, I have used elements of my analog photographic work as a bits and pieces of some layers.  These photographic works are chemigrams, and are generative in their own right, arising from semi-controlled chemical reactions on dark room paper in the presence of resists and light. These chemigrams are the first topos of my being, and bringing them into this work emphasizes something I have long wanted to pursue - the rich interplay of my analog and digital practices in search of unexplored territory.

Explore some territory - you just might find the quadrangle of your being.

Collection Mechanics:
In the initial week after launch, holders of any of my past fx(hash) projects may mint free editions to the extent of their reserves on a first come, first served basis.  Beginning in the 2nd week, any unclaimed editions will be offered for public sale. 

Minting Instructions: 
1) Use the Randomized Params button to explore outputs.  
2) When a design emerges that you want to mint, lock the Seed Input param.  
3) Mint & enjoy. 

Parameter Descriptions: 
Seed Input: Each output is a unique result based on your wallet address and the seed value. If you record the seed for a given output as you explore, you can simply type in the recorded seed to retrieve it.

Project Details:
Created by Wanda Oliver (wandaoliver.tez) in July, 2023, this work is licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

The minter shares secondary royalties with the creator and a beneficiary.

Interactions:
Press [D] in live mode to download.
Press [S] in live mode to download a high resolution output suitable for framing.
Press [F] in live mode to toggle the frame on and off.

metadata.name: Inefficient Ways of Independence #17
metadata.description:
"Inefficient Ways of Independence" is a thought - provoking artwork that explores the relationship between technology and the human experience.

The piece features a collection of iconic symbols of old technology, such as closed - circuit TV cameras, floppy disks, and vintage Mac computers, coupled together by a flow of particles.

The use of human body parts or heads adds a personal touch to the work, highlighting the intimate connection between the individual and technology.

The title "Inefficient Ways of Independence" serves as a commentary on our dependence on technology and the way that it has changed over time.

It also raises questions about our relationship with technology and the limitations that it can impose.

The piece invites the viewer to consider how technology has shaped our lives and to reflect on the consequences of our reliance on it.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT

metadata.name: Miniscapes #264
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)
